5. State verbs - Talk about opinions and feelings

a character
In general, there are more male than female characters in movies.

a director
In Hollywood, only about 5% of directors are women.

a director - a person who tells actors how to play their parts
a character - a person in a film

In general, there are more male than female characters in movies.

the cast
The cast of a typical Hollywood movie is still mainly white.
"Cast" means the actors and actresses in a film/play/show.

a plot
It's still very rare to see a movie plot with a disabled character.

1% - LGBT characters in movies
2.7% - movie characters with disabilities
18% - Latino population in US

Only 32% of speaking characters in movies are female.

Although the representation of the Black and Asian communities is getting 
better, the cast rarely has Latino characters.
"Genre" means a type of movie, e.g. comedy, horror.

She is critical of the current situation.
She says "it doesn‚Äôt seem right", 
"I think we all agree it‚Äôs not enough", and "I believe it‚Äôs not fair".

State verbs
State verbs describe states (opinions, states and senses) not actions 
and they don't usually take the continuous form.

Example
I think/I'm thinking we all agree it's not enough.

opinions
to agree, to believe, to seem, to understand, to think

feelings
to hate, to like, to want

senses
to look, to see

The numbers don't seem right in a country where 18.7% of the population has a disability.
In this sentence, "seem" is a state verb of opinion. It can't be used in the continuous form.

I believe it‚Äôs not fair.
In this sentence, "believe" is a state verb of opinion. It can't be used in the continuous form.

We see LGBT characters in only 1% of movies.
"See" is a state verb of senses and it doesn't normally take "-ing".

You're speaking very fast. correct
I'm not understanding you. incorrect
We can use "to speak" in the "-ing" (continuous) form, but not the state verb "to understand".

Look! The camera is showing the main character. He looks just like you.
"Show" is an action verb and "look" in this context is a state verb and doesn't take "-ing".

Do we agree that we need disabled characters in movies?
"Agree" is a state verb and it doesn't take "-ing".

She wants to be a director now.
The sentence is about "now" but we don't use the continuous form with the verb "want".

I hate how Hollywood movies don't represent my community.
"Hate" is a state verb that usually doesn't take "-ing".

